The `debounce` function limits a function's execution rate, ensuring it's only called once every specified interval.

```javascript
function debounce(func, delay) {
  let timeout;

  return function () {
    const context = this;
    const args = arguments;

    clearTimeout(timeout);
    timeout = setTimeout(function () {
      func.apply(context, args);
    }, delay);
  };
}

// Example usage
const searchInput = document.querySelector('#searchInput');
const fetchResults = debounce(function (query) {
  console.log(`Searching for "${query}"...`);
  // Simulate fetching results from an API
}, 500);

searchInput.addEventListener('input', function () {
  fetchResults(this.value);
});
```

In this example, the `debounce` function is used to limit the rate at which the `fetchResults` function is called as the user types in a search input field, preventing excessive API requests.
